::USGOV-U01-L01-Q01::Which statement best explains the main purpose of government? {
~To remove all rules from society#Incorrect. Government exists to create structure, not remove all rules.
~To allow every person to make separate laws#Incorrect. Government creates shared laws for society rather than separate laws for each person.
=To maintain order, provide services, and make decisions for society#Correct. This matches the lesson focus on order, services, and decision-making.
~To prevent communities from working together#Incorrect. Government helps organize society and support cooperation.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q02::Which example shows government providing a public service? {
~A student chooses a favorite hobby#Incorrect. A personal hobby is not a government service.
=A city maintains roads and transportation systems#Correct. Roads and transportation are examples of public services.
~A family decides what to cook for dinner#Incorrect. That is a private household decision, not a public service.
~A friend sends a text message#Incorrect. Sending a text is not a government service.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q03::How does government help maintain order? {
=By creating and enforcing rules#Correct. The lesson explains that governments maintain order through rules and laws.
~By removing all laws and expectations#Incorrect. Removing laws would reduce order, not maintain it.
~By encouraging confusion in communities#Incorrect. Government is meant to organize society, not confuse it.
~By preventing all decisions from being made#Incorrect. Governments make decisions to help society function.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q04::Why would society struggle without government? {
=There would likely be less structure and stability#Correct. The lesson explains that government provides structure, order, and stability.
~There would automatically be more fairness#Incorrect. The lesson does not suggest fairness increases automatically without government.
~There would be no need for public services#Incorrect. Public services are still necessary and are often organized by government.
~People would no longer need rules#Incorrect. Rules are still necessary for organized society.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q05::Which statement is most accurate? {
~Government only exists to punish people#Incorrect. The lesson includes services and decision-making, not only punishment.
~Government has no effect on daily life#Incorrect. Government affects daily life through laws, services, and decisions.
~Government should never make decisions for communities#Incorrect. Governments do make decisions that affect communities.
=Government organizes society and helps communities function#Correct. This reflects the central idea of the lesson.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q06::Which action best shows government providing protection? {
=A town funds firefighters and emergency responders#Correct. Protection includes public safety systems such as emergency response.
~A family plans a weekend trip#Incorrect. A family trip is a private choice, not a protection function of government.
~A student picks a favorite song#Incorrect. Personal preferences are not government protection.
~A store changes its window display#Incorrect. A display change is not an example of government protection.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q07::Why do governments form? {
~To keep people from ever working together#Incorrect. Governments help organize cooperation rather than stop it.
=To provide structure, order, and support for the common life of a community#Correct. Governments form to create organization and stability in society.
~To make all personal decisions for every citizen#Incorrect. Governments affect society, but they do not make every personal choice.
~To eliminate the need for communities#Incorrect. Communities still matter, and governments help them function.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q08::A city sets speed limits near schools. Which government function does this best show? {
~Providing entertainment#Incorrect. Speed limits are not a form of entertainment.
~Removing all risk from society#Incorrect. Government reduces danger, but it cannot remove all risk.
=Maintaining order and protecting people#Correct. Traffic rules help organize behavior and improve safety.
~Encouraging people to ignore laws#Incorrect. Speed limits are laws people are expected to follow.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q09::Which statement best describes how government affects daily life? {
~Government affects daily life only during elections#Incorrect. Government influences daily life through laws, services, and safety systems every day.
~Government affects daily life only when citizens ask for help#Incorrect. Government structures daily life even when people are not making requests.
~Government affects daily life only in large cities#Incorrect. Government affects communities of many sizes.
=Government affects daily life through rules, services, and public safety systems#Correct. This matches the lesson's examples of how government functions in society.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q10::Which example best shows a society using government to solve a shared problem? {
=A community creates trash collection and road maintenance systems#Correct. Government often organizes services that help everyone in a community.
~A student decides to study alone after school#Incorrect. That is an individual choice, not a shared public problem solved by government.
~A family chooses a movie to watch at home#Incorrect. That is a private decision, not a community-wide issue.
~A friend buys a new pair of shoes#Incorrect. Shopping is a personal action, not a government solution.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q11::Which situation best explains why laws matter in a community? {
~Laws make it unnecessary for people to cooperate#Incorrect. Laws support cooperation; they do not replace it.
=Laws give people shared expectations that help keep order#Correct. Shared rules help communities function in a predictable way.
~Laws remove the need for services#Incorrect. Communities still need services such as roads and safety systems.
~Laws guarantee that no one will ever disagree#Incorrect. Laws help manage society, but they do not end all disagreement.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q12::Which statement best explains the connection between government and public services? {
~Public services are created only for private households#Incorrect. Public services are organized for the community, not just one household.
~Public services matter only during emergencies#Incorrect. Services such as roads and schools matter every day.
=Government often organizes services that help a whole community function#Correct. The lesson highlights roads, schools, and safety systems as examples.
~Government avoids providing services so people stay independent#Incorrect. A key function of government is providing public services.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q13::A government builds roads and enforces traffic laws. What is the best explanation of this action? {
~It is trying to remove all personal responsibility#Incorrect. Government rules do not remove all personal responsibility.
~It is trying to stop people from traveling#Incorrect. Roads and traffic laws support safe travel rather than stop it.
~It is acting only as a punishment system#Incorrect. Building roads and setting traffic laws go beyond punishment.
=It is helping society by providing services and maintaining order#Correct. Roads are services, and traffic laws help keep order.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q14::What is one reason communities need government? {
=Communities need organization for decisions that affect everyone#Correct. Government helps organize shared decisions for the whole community.
~Communities should avoid any shared rules#Incorrect. Shared rules are part of how communities stay organized.
~Communities can function best when no one coordinates services#Incorrect. Communities need coordination for services and safety.
~Communities need government only for sporting events#Incorrect. Government serves broader needs such as order, protection, and services.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q15::Which example best shows government making decisions for society? {
~A child chooses a bedtime#Incorrect. A bedtime is a private household decision, not a public decision.
=A city council decides where to place a new stop sign#Correct. That is a community decision made through government.
~A student chooses a seat in class#Incorrect. Choosing a seat is not a government action.
~A family picks a restaurant for dinner#Incorrect. That is a private choice, not a public decision.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q16::What would likely happen if a community had no system for rules or services? {
~People would instantly agree on every issue#Incorrect. Without systems, disagreement and confusion would still exist.
~Public safety would improve on its own#Incorrect. Safety systems usually require organization and support.
=The community would face more confusion and less stability#Correct. The lesson explains that government helps create order and stability.
~Daily life would become easier for everyone#Incorrect. Without rules and services, daily life would usually become harder.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q17::Which statement best explains why roads and schools are mentioned in this lesson? {
~They are private hobbies supported by families#Incorrect. Roads and schools are not private hobbies.
~They show that government should control every part of life#Incorrect. The lesson shows government provides important services, not total control over life.
~They prove that rules are more important than services#Incorrect. The lesson includes both rules and services as parts of government.
=They are examples of services government often helps provide for the public#Correct. Roads and schools are concrete examples of public services.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q18::Which statement best explains the purpose of public safety systems? {
=They help protect people and support order in the community#Correct. Public safety systems are part of government's role in protection and order.
~They replace every law in society#Incorrect. Safety systems work alongside laws; they do not replace them.
~They remove the need for roads and schools#Incorrect. Communities still need many other services.
~They exist mainly to entertain citizens#Incorrect. Public safety systems serve protection, not entertainment.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q19::Why is shared decision-making important in government? {
~It allows every person to ignore community needs#Incorrect. Government decisions are meant to address shared needs, not ignore them.
=It helps communities organize choices that affect many people#Correct. Government helps make decisions for the good of the wider community.
~It removes the need for any public services#Incorrect. Decisions and services are both part of government.
~It keeps laws from applying to daily life#Incorrect. Government decisions often shape rules that affect daily life.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q20::Which example best shows order being maintained? {
~A student forgets a homework assignment#Incorrect. Forgetting homework is not an example of government maintaining order.
~A family changes weekend plans#Incorrect. Changing private plans is not a government function.
=A community follows traffic rules at busy intersections#Correct. Traffic rules help keep movement safe and organized.
~A neighbor paints a fence a new color#Incorrect. Painting a fence is not an example of public order.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q21::Which statement best explains why government is needed even when people want to cooperate? {
~Cooperation makes public services unnecessary#Incorrect. Even cooperative communities still need organized services and rules.
~Cooperation means laws should never exist#Incorrect. Laws still help provide structure in a cooperative society.
~Government is needed only when people are in conflict#Incorrect. Government also organizes services and shared decisions.
=Government helps organize cooperation through rules, services, and decisions#Correct. Cooperation works better when there is structure and organization.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q22::A town adds streetlights and creates safety rules for crosswalks. Which answer best describes this? {
~The town is removing all structure from daily life#Incorrect. Streetlights and safety rules add structure rather than remove it.
~The town is acting only to punish people#Incorrect. The example shows services and safety measures, not only punishment.
~The town is avoiding responsibility for public safety#Incorrect. The example shows the town taking responsibility for safety.
=The town is providing services and helping protect the public#Correct. Streetlights are a service, and crosswalk rules support protection.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q23::Which question is Lesson 01 most directly helping students answer? {
~How do citizens vote in federal elections?#Incorrect. Voting procedures are not the central focus of Lesson 01.
=What is government and why does it matter in society?#Correct. Lesson 01 focuses on the purpose of government and its basic functions.
~How do court cases become constitutional precedents?#Incorrect. Court precedent is beyond the scope of Lesson 01.
~What makes one political party stronger than another?#Incorrect. Political parties are not the lesson focus here.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q24::Which statement best summarizes why governments create laws? {
~To make every person think the same way#Incorrect. Laws organize behavior, but they do not make everyone think the same way.
~To remove the need for public services#Incorrect. Services are still needed even when laws exist.
=To provide order and guide how people live together in society#Correct. Laws help create structure and stability in a community.
~To keep communities from solving problems together#Incorrect. Laws can support organized problem solving.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q25::Without government, society would likely have more difficulty maintaining order and stability. {
=TRUE#Correct. The lesson explains that government helps societies maintain order, structure, and stability.
~FALSE#Incorrect. Lesson 01 teaches that government supports order and stability in society.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q26::Providing roads, schools, and public safety systems is one way government serves a community. {
=TRUE#Correct. These are examples of public services discussed in the lesson.
~FALSE#Incorrect. Lesson 01 identifies roads, schools, and public safety systems as government services.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q27::Government exists mainly to remove all rules from society. {
~TRUE#Incorrect. Lesson 01 explains that government creates and enforces rules to maintain order.
=FALSE#Correct. Government helps create structure through laws and shared rules.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q28::Traffic rules are one example of how government helps organize daily life. {
=TRUE#Correct. Traffic rules are a clear example of government maintaining order in a community.
~FALSE#Incorrect. Lesson 01 uses rules such as traffic laws to show how government organizes society.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q29::A government that provides services and enforces laws has no effect on everyday life. {
~TRUE#Incorrect. Government affects daily life through services, rules, and public safety systems.
=FALSE#Correct. Lesson 01 emphasizes that government plays an important role in everyday community life.
}

::USGOV-U01-L01-Q30::One reason governments form is to help communities make decisions that affect everyone. {
=TRUE#Correct. Government helps communities organize shared decisions that shape public life.
~FALSE#Incorrect. Lesson 01 teaches that shared decision-making is one reason government matters.
}
